<subsection xml:id="subsec-reading-tables-of-trigonometric-ratios-for-acute-angles" >
    <title>Reading Tables of Trigonometric Ratios For Acute Angles</title>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-table-of-tangents">
        <title>Table of Tangents</title>
        <image source="/natural-tangent.png">
            <shortdescription>Table of Natural Tangents</shortdescription>
        </image>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Follow the steps below to read the table of natural tangents for acute angles.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (i) Look at the column headed <m>x^\circ</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (ii) Start from the top and move downwards till you reach <m>5</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (iii) Move to the right in the row of <m>5</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.2</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                           (iv) Read the value in the cell where the row and column meet. 
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the table of natural tangents to find the value of the following angles.
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    (a) <m>\tan 4.0^\circ</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    (b) <m>\tan 3.2^\circ</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    (c) <m>\tan 2.37^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
              (a)  Go to tangent tables, look for angle <m>4.0^\circ</m>, and move to the column for <m>0.0</m>.
                The value is <m>0.0699</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore <m>\tan 4.0^\circ = 0.0699</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (b)  Go to tangent tables, look for angle <m>3^\circ</m>, and move to the column for <m>0.2</m>.
                The value is <m>0.0559</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore <m>\tan 3.2^\circ = 0.0559</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (c) (i) Go to tangent tables, look for angle <m> 2^\circ</m>, and move to the column for <m>0.3</m>.
                The value is <m>0.0402</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (ii) Move Horizontally to the right in the row of <m>2.3</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.7</m>. Read the number in the cell where the row and column meet and add to <m>0.0419</m>.
                  The value is <m>0.0402 + 0.0012 = 0.0414</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore <m>\tan 2.37^\circ = 0.0414</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
 </subsubsection>

 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-table-of-sines">
    <title>Table of Sines</title>
    <image source="/natural-sine.png">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Follow the steps below to read the table of natural sines for acute angles.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (i) Look at the column headed <m>x^\circ</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (ii) Start from the top and move downwards till you reach <m>5</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (iii) Move to the right in the row of <m>5</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.2</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                           (iv) Read the value in the cell where the row and column meet. 
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the table of natural sines to find the value of <m>\sin 3.81^\circ</m>..
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                 (i) Go to sine tables, look for angle <m>3^\circ</m>, and move to the column for <m>0.8</m>. The value is <m>0.0663</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (ii) Move Horizontally to the right in the row of <m>3.8</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.1</m>. Read the number in the cell where the row and column meet and add to <m>0.0523</m>.i.e
                <m>0.0663 + 0.0002 = 0.0665</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore <m>\sin 3.81^\circ = 0.0665</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

 </subsubsection>

 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-table-of-cosines">
    <title>Table of Cosines</title>
    <image source="/natural-cosines.png">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>  
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Follow the steps below to read the table of natural cosines for acute angles.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (i) Look at the column headed <m>x^\circ</m>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (ii) Move down the column until you reach the row for <m>4^\circ</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (iii) Move to the right in the row of <m>4^\circ</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.0</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (iv) Read the value in the cell where the row and column meet. 
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your work with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use cosine tables to find the value of the following angles.
            </p>

            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    (a) <m>\cos 2.5^\circ</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    (b) <m>\cos 3.24^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                (a) (i) Go to cosine tables
            </p>

            <p>
                (ii) Look for angle <m>2^\circ</m>, and move across to the column for <m>0.5</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (iii) The value is <m>0.9990</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore <m>\cos 2.5^\circ = 0.9990</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (b) (i) Go to cosine tables
            </p>

            <p>
                (ii) Look for angle <m>3^\circ</m>, and move across to the column for <m>0.2</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (iii) The value is <m>0.9984</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                (iv) Move horizontally to the right in the row of <m>3.2</m> and reach the column headed <m>0.4</m>. Read the number in the cell where the row and column meet and subtract from <m>0.9984</m>.i.e
                <m>0.9984 - 0.0000 = 0.9984</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore <m>\cos 3.24^\circ = 0.9984</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

